In this article, President Biden addresses ongoing budget negotiations with congressional leaders and emphasizes that defaulting on the national debt is not an option. He highlights that the negotiations are about the outlines of the budget, not about default. Biden expresses his disagreement with House Republicans who passed a bill making cuts to important programs relied upon by working- and middle-class Americans. He proposes a plan to cut spending by over $1 trillion and make the wealthy pay their fair share to reduce the deficit. Biden introduces General Charles Q. Brown, Jr. as his nominee for the next Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, praising his experience and leadership. He emphasizes the need to maintain a combat-credible force and stay competitive in an age of emerging technologies. Biden urges the Senate to confirm General Brown with bipartisan support. The article concludes with Biden acknowledging the sacrifices made by military families and celebrating the diversity and strength of the Armed Forces.